WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
&gt;&gt;Dr. Susan Kleiner: I walked into this building,
it's like the good mood building; colors and

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:06.290
it's so g-o-o-d.

00:00:06.290 --> 00:00:08.960
[laughs] Google, right.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:16.880
So it is great to be here, I'm thrilled to
be on the Google campus in my backyard and

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:24.880
it's just so nice to know that your whole
programming here is starting to center around

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:26.070
health and fitness.

00:00:26.070 --> 00:00:33.550
At lunch we were talking about that it's time
to take a stand, that if we don't have health

00:00:33.550 --> 00:00:39.710
we don't have the fundamental tools to progress,
to proceed, and certainly to excel.

00:00:39.710 --> 00:00:42.860
So health is critically important.

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:51.360
What I have learned in the years of being
a sports nutritionist is that health is great

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.750
but we have very important performance goals
that we also want to accomplish.

00:00:55.750 --> 00:00:59.320
Wouldn't it be great if those could overlap?

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:05.170
And most people really want to be happy, that's
what everybody wants.

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:08.490
What was interesting to me when I said to
you, "How do you feel?" is that there was,

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:13.650
you know, like one or two who said "good,"
I heard happy, but everybody else was kind

00:01:13.650 --> 00:01:15.030
of quiet.

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:20.170
And you know it's very interesting when I
go into an elementary school and I ask the

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:27.680
kids, "Tell me how do you feel?" they right
away can tell me, "I feel happy, I have ants

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:34.990
in my pants, I have too much energy, I'm sleepy,"
they yell it out with no inhibition at all.

00:01:34.990 --> 00:01:40.860
I go to a middle school and I say, "How do
you feel?" and they all look at each other.

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:41.860
[chuckles]

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:42.860
[laughter]

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:46.350
And once somebody says something then they've
all got permission to say something and they

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:52.430
all can pretty much say to me as well how
they're feeling at that moment, they are connected.

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:58.050
Many of them will say they're tired, many
of them will say a little anxious, some of

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:03.300
them say that they're very happy, they're
starting to have some different feelings at

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:04.770
that point.

00:02:04.770 --> 00:02:10.440
When I get to high school it gets a little
quieter, certainly when I get to colleges

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:17.750
and definitely work settings it gets quieter
and quieter.

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:27.590
People are less willing to express how they
feel or are becoming more and more disconnected

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:29.840
from how they feel.

00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:34.730
Just as we've talked about in the nutrition
field for decades that Americans are disconnected

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:40.879
from the neck down, that when we walk by plate
glass windows we don't look at ourselves,

00:02:40.879 --> 00:02:45.430
we have mirrors from the neck up, we don't
wanna know what we look like from the neck

00:02:45.430 --> 00:02:46.430
down.

00:02:46.430 --> 00:02:52.530
We are also encouraged by our society to disconnect
from the neck up.

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:54.850
You're too tired?

00:02:54.850 --> 00:02:56.400
Take some caffeine.

00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:58.200
You're sad?

00:02:58.200 --> 00:02:59.510
Take a pill.

00:02:59.510 --> 00:03:00.690
You're overworked?

00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:04.190
Too bad, keep going.

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:08.390
You don't have time to exercise because it
makes you feel better?

00:03:08.390 --> 00:03:11.540
Well you really better get to work and make
a dollar.

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:19.580
So we are being encouraged to ignore how we
feel, but how we feel is in fact what it's

00:03:19.580 --> 00:03:21.370
all about.

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:28.610
And so I encourage you to look at my faces
up here [chuckles] and when I put this together

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:35.709
and this is stuff that I love, serendipity,
these are actually all up there alphabetically,

00:03:35.709 --> 00:03:41.489
but you'll notice that all the ones in the
center are the happy ones.

00:03:41.489 --> 00:03:47.860
Nobody wants to be on the outside team, everyone
wants to be on the inside and everyone wants

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:50.480
to be confident, happy, and optimistic.

00:03:50.480 --> 00:04:00.930
And in fact what you eat has a huge impact
on whether you're on the inside or the outside,

00:04:00.930 --> 00:04:09.459
whether you're feeling good, happy, optimistic,
confident, or you're feeling anger, anxiety,

00:04:09.459 --> 00:04:17.470
not coping well, sad; what you eat plays a
profound role in how you feel.

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:22.049
So I love this, Will Rogers says, "You know
you've got to exercise your brain just like

00:04:22.049 --> 00:04:23.049
your muscles."

00:04:23.049 --> 00:04:29.960
And we talk about this and you have to feed
your brain just like you have to feed your

00:04:29.960 --> 00:04:30.960
muscles.

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:40.170
These athletes no matter how well trained,
how genetically gifted, how well skilled and

00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:47.970
drilled they are, if they can't get out of
bed in the morning because they're depressed

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:54.330
it doesn't matter how hard they've trained;
they can't get to the starting line let alone

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:55.860
the finish line.

00:04:55.860 --> 00:05:02.290
And the beginning of The Good Mood Diet, actually
the kernel of the beginning of the thought

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:08.680
of The Good Mood Diet came from when I did
work with a very high profile, very elite

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:13.680
athlete who couldn't get out of bed in the
morning and was being paid a boat load of

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:16.150
money to show up.

00:05:16.150 --> 00:05:23.710
So what I found at that time and what I've
continued to preach and work on in my practice

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:26.470
is that you must feed your brain.

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:36.130
That in fact if it was all about what we weighed,
which is what society tells us, everyone needs

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:41.530
to get on the scale and pay attention to what
you weigh, that the goal is weight loss, that

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:47.180
we all should weigh less and we all should
be thinking about weighing less.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:55.110
If that's really what mattered to us in how
we felt, we would all be thin.

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:57.699
We know that diets work.

00:05:57.699 --> 00:06:05.620
But we go on a diet, it makes us feel bad
and it doesn't matter if you've lost weight.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:08.680
You go off of it.

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:14.850
So what The Good Mood Diet is, is the blending
of cutting edge sports nutrition, although

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:19.789
I kind of hide it in there because if I talk
too much about sports nutrition it would scare

00:06:19.789 --> 00:06:26.150
everybody away, but nobody knows how to help
people alter their body composition, gain

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:29.259
muscle, lose fat like a sports nutritionist.

00:06:29.259 --> 00:06:36.260
But blended with cutting edge neurobiology
of food is what I call it; the neuroscience

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:37.260
of food.

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:44.759
How food affects the health of the brain,
mood, cognitive function, our ability to rest

00:06:44.759 --> 00:06:50.950
and relax, our ability to have the mental
energy and focus when we need it; when you

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:57.710
blend those it's a powerful force to make
you feel the difference.

00:06:57.710 --> 00:07:06.520
So that when you follow this kind of concept
and then you go off of it, it's not about

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:11.580
what's happening with your weight that changes
you, because any of you who have tried to

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:16.259
lose weight know that it takes a long time
before you say, "Oh I really outta try and

00:07:16.259 --> 00:07:18.430
lose this weight again."

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:23.690
What happens with The Good Mood Diet is that
within weeks you've realized that you feel

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:26.300
so bad you can't wait to be back on the diet.

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:31.210
And this is what I learned from clients and
from Good Mood Diet groups around the city

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:33.520
and the country as I did this.

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:39.620
So conceptually we think about feeding your
brain because most of us eat by default, you

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:45.410
can't eat this, you can't eat that, you can't
eat the next thing, don't eat, avoid, limit,

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:48.349
those are the language of the diet world.

00:07:48.349 --> 00:07:56.470
And so whatever's left over is what ends up
on your plate which isn't very fun, it isn't

00:07:56.470 --> 00:08:01.919
very inspirational, and it probably doesn't
taste very good either so nobody wants to

00:08:01.919 --> 00:08:02.990
do that.

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:08.450
A typical weight loss diet is very low in
calories, it's so low in calories I always

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:14.020
say it wouldn't feed a small pigeon and in
fact the foods that you particularly are told

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:19.289
to avoid make those diets depressing.

00:08:19.289 --> 00:08:26.539
Not depressing because, gee, you wish you
could eat other food, it's because in fact

00:08:26.539 --> 00:08:29.780
they are biochemically depressing.

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:31.060
So let's talk about that.

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:38.110
I'm gonna do a little bit of a science course
here very quickly because I'm an educator

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:43.930
and a motivator and I know that when you reach
a certain point and you don't understand why

00:08:43.930 --> 00:08:50.180
you're doing something you stop, but if you
understand why you keep going, you can make

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:52.040
the choice to keep going.

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:54.480
So did anybody ever play with a chemistry
set?

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:59.050
Yeah, and I almost burned down my parents'
basement with the chemistry set [laughs] at

00:08:59.050 --> 00:09:01.000
one time in my life.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:06.360
But think of your body as a chemistry set;
we are kind of this bag of chemicals.

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:14.510
And so food is the chemistry that enters our
body; our stomach is kinda that Erlenmeyer

00:09:14.510 --> 00:09:19.830
flask and your metabolism is the Bunsen burner
underneath.

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:25.810
So when you eat the food goes into your stomach
and you shake it around and you have your

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:33.990
metabolic rate going and it ends up going
into your blood stream, digested, absorbed

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:35.130
into your blood stream.

00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:39.710
What do you think the very first organ is
that's affected by the food that you eat?

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:40.830
Just yell it out.

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:41.950
&gt;&gt; female #1: The brain.

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:45.820
&gt;&gt;Dr. Susan Kleiner: The brain, right, see
I know I got a smart group here.

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:50.089
Most people say the liver, the heart, no the
brain.

00:09:50.089 --> 00:09:56.959
In fact I want you to think about this because
it's so incredible: you don't even have to

00:09:56.959 --> 00:10:01.160
even swallow the food for it to affect your
brain.

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:09.230
Think about when you get really hungry and
you haven't eaten maybe for hours, you put

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:17.330
something in your mouth and you're chewing
it and you just go, "Ah I feel so much better,

00:10:17.330 --> 00:10:18.870
I'm eating."

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:24.740
Well it didn't even hit your stomach yet and
you're brain is affected by the fact that

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:27.170
you've put food in your mouth.

00:10:27.170 --> 00:10:34.890
So imagine the power of eating the right foods,
the right combinations of foods at the right

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:38.680
times and the impact that those can have on
your brain.

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:40.920
So mechanisms of mood.

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:50.160
Well mood is very complex, it occurs in many,
by a sort of a synergy of changes in several

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:58.330
different parts of the brain and the neurotransmitters
are sort of the connectors, the chemicals

00:10:58.330 --> 00:11:05.440
that connect and communicate from one brain
cell to the next; in fact from one cell in

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:09.180
the central nervous system to every other
cell in the central nervous system.

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:12.550
But we're talking about mood, what goes on
in the brain.

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:18.100
Serotonin, now there are a number of different
neurotransmitters, we're going to focus on

00:11:18.100 --> 00:11:25.050
serotonin today because it is the most abundant
neurotransmitter that influences mood, it

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:29.420
is also probably one of the most well understood.

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:37.110
You know serotonin by anti-depressant drugs
today, they always are trying to raise serotonin

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:38.830
levels in the brain.

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:43.640
Shift to what is the building block of serotonin
in the brain?

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:44.720
Tryptophan.

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:50.500
Tryptophan is an amino acid, comes in from
protein, it is essential in the diet, we cannot

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:57.250
manufacture enough of it in the body, it is
the building block of serotonin in the brain;

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.730
it's found in the blood, the precursor to
serotonin.

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:06.470
Now we know that tryptophan is essential to
raise serotonin levels in the brain because

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:11.769
if we deplete the body from tryptophan then
serotonin levels drop.

00:12:11.769 --> 00:12:17.620
And all this kind of connection is important
because what I talk about is evidence based,

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:27.769
meaning that it's scientifically supported;
the data are there for the information that

00:12:27.769 --> 00:12:32.610
I'm giving you here today and what's written
in The Good Mood Diet.

00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:33.910
[pause]

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:40.940
So if tryptophan is what is required to raise
serotonin levels in the brain, it is the building

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:49.250
block, then one would assume that a very high
protein diet should raise your mood.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:56.300
In most instances diets that are very high
in protein and very low in carb do the opposite.

00:12:56.300 --> 00:13:00.800
You wouldn't wanna work for anybody who was
on a very high protein low carb diet, you

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:05.740
wouldn't wanna be married to anybody that
was on that diet, you wouldn't wanna have

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:12.899
to partner with anybody at work on that diet
because it actually lowers serotonin levels

00:13:12.899 --> 00:13:14.810
in most people.

00:13:14.810 --> 00:13:23.959
People become angry, aggressive, depressed,
poor coping skills, all of those happen yet

00:13:23.959 --> 00:13:27.250
we have an abundance of tryptophan.

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:28.440
Why?

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:29.630
[pause]

00:13:29.630 --> 00:13:30.630
Well --

00:13:30.630 --> 00:13:31.630
[pause]

00:13:31.630 --> 00:13:38.030
amazingly, and I always borrow a phrase, it's
the carbohydrates stupid, [chuckles] is what

00:13:38.030 --> 00:13:44.570
you'll read in The Good Mood Diet because
in fact it is the carbohydrate in your diet

00:13:44.570 --> 00:13:50.930
that allows tryptophan to cross the blood
brain barrier and enter the brain.

00:13:50.930 --> 00:13:56.760
Now you know this, you know this in your gut,
you know this fundamentally.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:14:05.120
What ingredient, what single food makes you
feel really good really fast?

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:07.519
&gt;&gt;male #1: Sugar.

00:14:07.519 --> 00:14:08.519
[pause]

00:14:08.519 --> 00:14:09.920
Sugar, right.

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:14.650
So don't ever let anybody tell you that sugar
doesn't make you feel good.

00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:21.620
Now we're gonna talk about why too much sugar
is on my Feel-Bad Foods list, but understand

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:28.350
the science and why in the short term sugar
makes you feel so good.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:33.960
Now you know it's very simple, it's very rapidly
digested and enters the blood stream.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:41.730
When carbohydrate levels go up, when blood
sugar goes up, insulin, the hormone that helps

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:50.000
take blood sugar out of the blood and transfer
it into the muscles or to the liver, when

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:57.290
insulin goes up as well, it stimulates a whole
separate cascade of biochemical events that

00:14:57.290 --> 00:15:02.940
actually take out all the other competing
amino acids in the blood stream that compete

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:09.449
with tryptophan to cross the blood brain barrier
and they leave tryptophan out there all alone.

00:15:09.449 --> 00:15:15.410
There are seven other amino acids that resemble
tryptophan.

00:15:15.410 --> 00:15:22.519
Those seven other amino acids compete for
the same receptor molecule, the same usher

00:15:22.519 --> 00:15:25.490
that takes tryptophan into the brain.

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:32.760
And so when you have a very high protein diet
you have a lot of those competitive amino

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:41.529
acids around and those compete with tryptophan
and so a proportionately lower amount of tryptophan

00:15:41.529 --> 00:15:43.440
gets into the brain.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:49.880
If, on the other hand, you could remove those
competitive amino acids, which is what happens

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:54.880
when you eat carbohydrate and amazingly it
takes those amino acids and shuttles them

00:15:54.880 --> 00:16:00.510
to the muscle cell where we want the muscle
to recover, repair, and grow after exercise,

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:03.329
since we're all active.

00:16:03.329 --> 00:16:08.910
It leaves tryptophan out there with little
competition to enter into the brain and raise

00:16:08.910 --> 00:16:16.320
serotonin levels; this happens in an infinitesimal,
small amount of time.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:24.399
And so the sugar that you eat raises of course
not only serotonin, there are number of other

00:16:24.399 --> 00:16:30.709
neurotransmitters that are raised as well
that are too much for me to go into today.

00:16:30.709 --> 00:16:38.220
But when it comes to raising mood, carbohydrate
plays an enormously important role; so important

00:16:38.220 --> 00:16:43.910
that diets that are lower than 40 percent
of calories as carbohydrate have been shown

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:48.680
to be depressing, literally depressing.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:57.490
So ideally we should eat carbohydrate and
protein together; it is the ideal fuel and

00:16:57.490 --> 00:17:05.540
recovery combination for muscles, it is also
a beautiful combination for the brain, giving

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:11.640
you the tryptophan that you need and enhancing
the movement of tryptophan into the brain

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:13.240
to raise serotonin levels.

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:18.830
Well so I said sugar makes you feel good.

00:17:18.830 --> 00:17:22.970
Well then why do we keep telling people to
stop eating so much sugar?

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:30.470
Well this is why, and we've had a discussion
sort of nationally about insulin resistance.

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:35.160
That's something that if you have a lot of
sugar over a long period of time and you start

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:37.770
to gain weight, can happen.

00:17:37.770 --> 00:17:43.660
So over a long period of time you can develop
insulin resistance and move slowly into the

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:46.850
beginning of Type II diabetes.

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:49.770
However, that's long way off.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:56.370
What also happens when you eat a lot of sugar
frequently is that it is considered a stress

00:17:56.370 --> 00:17:57.580
by the body.

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:04.990
When your blood sugar levels rapidly rise
insulin meets it and lowers it and rises again

00:18:04.990 --> 00:18:10.650
and lowers it; your body responds with a stress
response to that.

00:18:10.650 --> 00:18:17.770
One of the results of the stress hormone response
is protein degradation, breaking down proteins.

00:18:17.770 --> 00:18:22.679
This is kind of part of that fight or flight
response, we're talking about a very short

00:18:22.679 --> 00:18:27.010
term, acute response to a stress.

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:34.429
And so if you begin to degrade proteins you
are flooding your bloodstream once again with

00:18:34.429 --> 00:18:39.400
lots and lots of protein and lowering the
serotonin level.

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:46.780
There you have to go back and eat more sugar
to then help move the tryptophan into the

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:54.370
brain and so you get on, in a very short period
of time, within four to five days, maximum

00:18:54.370 --> 00:19:03.620
seven days, your body will begin using other
neurotransmitters as well to force a craving

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:09.770
for more and more sugar so that you can raise
the serotonin levels over and over again.

00:19:09.770 --> 00:19:15.169
So in addition to the long term stress that
lots of sugar puts on your body this is a

00:19:15.169 --> 00:19:21.940
very acute short term stress and it's why
you begin on a daily basis to want more and

00:19:21.940 --> 00:19:25.480
more sugar because you want to raise your
mood.

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:29.800
It's a biological function, a biological urge.

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:36.130
This is not about do you have the willpower,
this is about making the choices that alter

00:19:36.130 --> 00:19:38.580
your physiological responses.

00:19:38.580 --> 00:19:45.920
So we go back to the foods that were served
in the cafeteria today; slow digesting, whole

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:50.350
carbohydrate, sources rich in carbohydrate.

